This paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it focuses on network embedding, which is a common task in social network analysis. It could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new framework for network embedding that incorporates random walk and personalized proximity preservation, which are common techniques in machine learning. Additionally, it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as it discusses the scalability of the proposed framework. It could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as network embedding is often used in information retrieval tasks. Finally, it could belong to cs.SD (Software Engineering) as it proposes a new framework for network embedding that could be implemented as software.
